data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false"). Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with useful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — shows both values on failure instead of just "false"
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections:
  - `CollectionAssert.Contains(collection, item)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(collection)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(collection)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — order-sensitive
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — order-insensitive
- **Message parameters** — always add a message string to `Assert.IsTrue` for LINQ-based checks so failures are diagnosable

**Bonus:** If you adopt **FluentAssertions** (popular NuGet package), you get even more expressive syntax:

```csharp
users.Should().HaveCount(3)
     .And.OnlyContain(u => u.IsActive)
     .And.ContainSingle(u => u.Role == "Admin");
```
